Princeton, New Jersey

The Municipality of Princeton is a [borough](/Borough_(New_Jersey)) located in [Mercer County, New Jersey](/Mercer_County,_New_Jersey), United States. It was officially established on January 1, 2013, as a result of the consolidation of the former [Borough of Princeton](/Borough_of_Princeton,_New_Jersey) and [Princeton Township](/Princeton_Township,_New_Jersey). This merger effectively dissolved both of the previously separate municipalities. According to the data from the [2020 United States census](/2020_United_States_census), the borough's population stood at 30,681, marking an increase of 2,109 individuals, or approximately 7.4%, compared to the combined population of 28,572 recorded in the [2010 census](/2010_United_States_census). Prior to this consolidation, the 2000 census indicated a total population of 30,230 for the two entities, with 14,204 residents residing in the borough and 16,027 in the township.

Princeton boasts a rich history that predates the [American Revolutionary War](/American_Revolutionary_War). The community is famously the home of [Princeton University](/Princeton_University), a globally recognized and highly acclaimed [research](/Research) institution. The university, which bears the town's name, relocated to Princeton in 1756 from its original location in [Newark, New Jersey](/Newark,_New_Jersey). While its association with the university is a primary factor in defining Princeton as a prominent [college town](/College_town), the area also hosts several other significant institutions. These include the prestigious [Institute for Advanced Study](/Institute_for_Advanced_Study), the [Princeton Plasma Physics Laboratory](/Princeton_Plasma_Physics_Laboratory), the [Princeton Theological Seminary](/Princeton_Theological_Seminary), the [Opinion Research Corporation](/Opinion_Research_Corporation), major corporations such as [Bristol-Myers Squibb](/Bristol-Myers_Squibb) and [Siemens Corporate Research](/Siemens_Corporate_Research), research organizations like [SRI International](/SRI_International), [FMC Corporation](/FMC_Corporation), the [Educational Testing Service](/Educational_Testing_Service), the [Robert Wood Johnson Foundation](/R._W._Johnson_Foundation), [Amrep Corporation](/Amrep_Corporation), [Church and Dwight](/Church_and_Dwight), [Berlitz International](/Berlitz_International), and [Dow Jones & Company](/Dow_Jones_%26_Company).

Strategically situated, Princeton is located approximately equidistant from the major metropolitan centers of [New York City](/New_York_City) and [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). Its proximity to critical transportation arteries such as [Interstate 95](/Interstate_95) and [U.S. Route 1](/U.S._Route_1) facilitates easy access to both cities. Consequently, Princeton receives significant television and radio broadcasts originating from both major urban areas. It is also geographically close to [Trenton, New Jersey](/Trenton,_New_Jersey), the state capital, as well as [New Brunswick, New Jersey](/New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey) and [Edison, New Jersey](/Edison,_New_Jersey).

Since 1945, Princeton has served as the official residence of the Governor of New Jersey. This began with [Morven](/Morven_(Princeton,_New_Jersey)), located within the former Princeton Borough, which became the state's first governor's mansion. In 1982, Morven was succeeded by the larger [Drumthwacket](/Drumthwacket), a colonial mansion situated in the former township. It's worth noting that not all governors have actually resided in these designated homes. Morven has since been transformed into a museum and garden, managed by the [New Jersey Historical Society](/New_Jersey_Historical_Society).

Historically, the community was divided into two distinct municipalities: a [township](/Township_(New_Jersey)) and a [borough](/Borough_(New_Jersey)), with the borough entirely enclosed by the township. The separation of the borough from the township occurred in 1894, stemming from a disagreement over school taxes. Subsequently, both municipalities collaborated in the [Princeton Public Schools](/Princeton_Public_Schools) district and shared certain public services before their eventual reunification in January 2013. The historical Princeton Borough encompassed [Nassau Street](/Nassau_Street_(Princeton)), the primary commercial artery, and a significant portion of the university campus, representing the urban core until the suburban expansion following World War II. The borough and township historically maintained roughly equivalent populations. Key thoroughfares within Princeton include Harrison, Witherspoon, Nassau, Bayard, Washington, and Stockton Streets.

History

Early History

The [Lenape](/Lenape) [Native Americans](/Native_Americans_in_the_United_States) were the initial known inhabitants of the region that now constitutes Princeton.

European settlement in the area commenced in the latter part of the 17th century, with settlers arriving from Delaware to establish communities in [West Jersey](/West_Jersey) and from New York to populate [East Jersey](/East_Jersey). The specific site destined to become Princeton was situated within a wilderness area between these two colonial provinces. Henry Greenland is recognized as the first European to establish a residence within the boundaries of what would become the municipality. He constructed his home in 1683, which also served as a tavern. This establishment became a meeting point for representatives from West and East Jersey as they convened to delineate the boundaries between their respective provinces. Greenland's son-in-law, Daniel Brimson, was residing in the area by 1690 and bequeathed property in a will dated 1696.

At that time, Princeton was known only as a part of the nearby settlement of [Stony Brook](/Stony_Brook_(Millstone_River)). Nathaniel Fitz Randolph, a native of the area, recorded in his private journal on December 28, 1758, that Princeton received its name in 1724. This naming coincided with the construction of the first house in the vicinity by James Leonard. Leonard, in his diary, referred to the nascent community as "Princetown" when describing the location of his expansive estate. Subsequently, the community was known by several names, including Princetown, Prince's Town, and finally, Princeton. The name Princeton first appeared in 1724 and became commonly used within the following decade. While official documentation is lacking, a prevalent theory suggests the municipality was named in honor of [Prince William of Orange](/William_III_of_England). Another hypothesis posits that the name originated from a prominent landowner named Henry Prince, who was the son-in-law of a well-known English merchant; however, there is no concrete evidence to support this claim. The association with a royal prince seems more probable, given that three nearby settlements bore names reflecting royalty: [Kingston, New Jersey](/Kingston,_New_Jersey), Queenstown (located near the intersection of Nassau and Harrison Streets), and Princessville (in Lawrence Township).

William Edward Schenck, writing in 1850, described Princeton as having achieved "no very considerable size" until the establishment of the College of New Jersey within its limits. Upon the death of Richard Stockton, one of the township's founders, in 1709, his estate was passed to his sons, who played a role in expanding the property holdings and increasing the population. According to the [1880 United States census](/1880_United_States_census), the population of Princeton, excluding students, was 3,209 individuals. The local population has seen consistent growth since the nineteenth century. The census of [2010](/2010_United_States_census) reported 12,307 inhabitants for Princeton Borough and 16,265 for Princeton Township. The population figures have shown relative stability; however, since the arrival of the College of New Jersey (now Princeton University) in 1756, the town's population experiences a noticeable increase each fall and winter, followed by a significant decline during the summer months.

Revolution

During the crucial [Battle of Princeton](/Battle_of_Princeton) in January 1777, [George Washington](/George_Washington)'s forces successfully compelled the British to withdraw from southern New Jersey. Following this victory, Princeton became the site of the first Legislature convened under the State Constitution, tasked with establishing the State's seal, selecting its governor, and organizing its governmental structure. Furthermore, two signatories of the Declaration of Independence—[Richard Stockton](/Richard_Stockton_(Continental_Congressman)) and [John Witherspoon](/John_Witherspoon)—were residents of Princeton. To honor their legacy, two streets in the downtown area were named in their memory.

On January 10, 1938, Henry Ewing Hale initiated a movement to establish the "Historical Society of Princeton." The Bainbridge House, constructed in 1766 by Job Stockton, was later dedicated for this purpose. This historic house had previously served as a meeting place for the [Continental Congress](/Continental_Congress) in 1783, functioned as a general office, and housed the Princeton Public Library. The house is currently owned by Princeton University and is leased to the Princeton Historical Society for a nominal fee of one dollar per year. The Bainbridge House has retained a significant portion of its original architectural features, including its staircase, flooring, and paneled walls, with approximately 70% of the structure remaining unaltered. Aside from necessary safety upgrades such as wheelchair accessibility and electrical system enhancements, the house has been meticulously restored to its original appearance and character.

Government History

Throughout significant periods of its history, Princeton was characterized as a strategic point along a major transportation route, lying on the boundary between [Somerset County, New Jersey](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey) and [Middlesex County, New Jersey](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey). This boundary followed the primary road connecting New York and Philadelphia, which is now known as Nassau Street. When Mercer County was established in 1838, a portion of [West Windsor](/West_Windsor,_New_Jersey) was incorporated into the section of [Montgomery Township](/Montgomery_Township,_New_Jersey) that fell within the new county, forming Princeton Township. Further adjustments occurred in 1853 when the area between the southern boundary of the former Borough and the [Delaware and Raritan Canal](/Delaware_and_Raritan_Canal) was annexed to Princeton Township. The Princeton Borough officially separated as a distinct municipality in 1894.

In the early 19th century, [New Jersey boroughs](/Borough_(New_Jersey)) operated as quasi-independent entities chartered within existing townships, lacking full municipal autonomy. Princeton Borough obtained such a charter in 1813, existing within Montgomery and West Windsor Townships. It remained part of Princeton Township until the enactment of the Borough Act of 1894. This legislation mandated that each township form a single school district. Rather than comply, Princeton Borough petitioned for separation. Notably, the two Princeton municipalities had already consolidated their public school systems in the decades leading up to the municipal merger. Minor boundary adjustments in 1928 and 1951 incorporated the sites of the Princeton Hospital and the Princeton Regional High School within the Borough's limits.

Geography

Princeton is situated just south of a prominent ridge known as Princeton Ridge. Due to its location in a lower-lying area, the municipality has occasionally experienced issues with cellular phone reception.

According to the [U.S. Census Bureau](/United_States_Census_Bureau), Princeton encompasses a total area of 18.41 square miles (47.69 km²). Of this total area, 17.95 square miles (46.48 km²) consist of land, and 0.47 square miles (1.21 km²) are water, representing 2.53% of the total area.

Several [unincorporated communities](/Unincorporated_area_(New_Jersey)), including [Cedar Grove, Mercer County, New Jersey](/Cedar_Grove,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey), [Port Mercer, New Jersey](/Port_Mercer,_New_Jersey), Princeton Basin, and Jugtown, have been integrated into the broader Princeton area over time, yet they continue to retain distinct community identities.

Princeton shares borders with the municipalities of [Hopewell Township, Mercer County, New Jersey](/Hopewell_Township,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey), [Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey](/Lawrence_Township,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey), and [West Windsor, New Jersey](/West_Windsor,_New_Jersey) within Mercer County. It also borders [Plainsboro Township, New Jersey](/Plainsboro_Township,_New_Jersey) and [South Brunswick Township, New Jersey](/South_Brunswick,_New_Jersey) in [Middlesex County, New Jersey](/Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), and [Franklin Township, Somerset County, New Jersey](/Franklin_Township,_Somerset_County,_New_Jersey) and [Montgomery Township, New Jersey](/Montgomery_Township,_New_Jersey) in [Somerset County, New Jersey](/Somerset_County,_New_Jersey).

The ZIP codes serving Princeton include 08540, 08541 (associated with the [Educational Testing Service](/Educational_Testing_Service)), 08542 (primarily covering the former Borough), 08543 (designated for [PO boxes](/PO_box)), and 08544 (serving the [University](/Princeton_University)).

