As of the [2010 United States census](/2010_United_States_census), the combined population of the borough and township was 28,572. [39][40]

According to data from the website Data USA, Princeton has a population of 30,168 individuals, of whom 85% are U.S. citizens. The ethnic composition of the population is as follows: 20,393 White residents (67.6%), 4,636 Asian residents (15.4%), 2,533 Hispanic residents (8.4%), 1,819 Black residents (6.03%), and 618 residents identifying as Two or More Races (2.05%). The most commonly spoken foreign languages in Princeton are Chinese (1,800 speakers), Spanish (1,429 speakers), and French (618 speakers). Notably, Princeton exhibits a relatively high number of speakers of Scandinavian languages (425 speakers), Italian (465 speakers), and German (1,000 speakers) when compared to other locales.

Government

Local Government

Princeton operates under the [borough](/Borough_(New_Jersey)) form of municipal government, a structure adopted by 218 of New Jersey's 564 municipalities, making it the most prevalent form of local governance in the state. [41] The governing body consists of a mayor and a borough council. All elected positions are [at-large](/At-large) and partisan, decided during the November general election. The mayor is directly elected by the voters for a four-year term. The borough council comprises six members, elected to three-year terms on a staggered basis, with two council seats up for election each year within a three-year cycle. The borough form of government, as implemented in Princeton, features a "[weak mayor](/Weak_mayor) / strong council" system. In this arrangement, the council members constitute the legislative branch, while the mayor presides over meetings and votes only in the event of a tie. The mayor possesses the power to veto ordinances, though this veto can be overridden by a two-thirds majority vote of the council. The mayor is also responsible for making committee and liaison assignments for council members, with most appointments requiring the advice and consent of the council. [42][43][44]

The mayor, serving as Princeton's chief executive officer, is directly elected for a four-year term. This role includes nominating individuals for various boards and commissions, subject to the council's approval. The mayor presides over council meetings and casts a vote in specific circumstances, such as tie votes. [44] The council, composed of six members serving three-year staggered terms, functions as the policy-making body and holds administrative powers. Council members approve mayoral appointments and participate in various boards and committees, acting as liaisons to specific departments or bodies. [44]

As of 2025, the [mayor of Princeton](/Mayor_of_Princeton,_New_Jersey) is Mark Freda, a member of the [Democratic Party (United States)](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)), whose current term concludes on December 31, 2028. [3][4] The Princeton Council members are Council President Mia Sacks (D, 2026), David F. Cohen (D, 2027), Leticia Fraga (D, 2027), Michelle Pirone Lambros (D, 2026), Leighton Newlin (D, 2027), and Brian McDonald (D, 2027). [45][46][47][48][49][50][51][52]

In 2018, Princeton recorded the highest average property tax bill in Mercer County, amounting to $19,388, which significantly exceeded the statewide average of $8,767. [53]

Merger of Borough and Township

Efforts to merge the borough and township of Princeton were ongoing for nearly fifty years, though they were initially unsuccessful. The first attempt at consolidation, made in 1953, saw 63% of township voters in favor of the merger, while 57% of borough voters opposed it. [54] Subsequent merger proposals were rejected by borough residents, largely due to the differing zoning requirements between the densely populated borough and the more spread-out properties of the surrounding township. A consolidation attempt in 1979 garnered 70% support in the township but narrowly failed in the borough by 33 votes, a result that was confirmed after a recount. [55][56][57] Despite township voters again endorsing a merger referendum in 1996 by a nearly 3–1 margin, approximately 57% of borough voters rejected the proposal, marking the sixth failed attempt at consolidation. [58]

The residents of both the Borough of Princeton and Princeton Township ultimately voted on November 8, 2011, to merge the two municipalities into a single entity. This referendum was notable for the increased encouragement and eligibility of university student voters to register and participate locally, a factor that likely contributed significantly to the measure's passage. The student vote, unburdened by homeowner concerns regarding zoning, was counted towards the borough's tally. In Princeton Borough, the vote was 1,385 in favor and 902 against. In Princeton Township, 3,542 voted in favor and 604 against. Proponents of the merger argued that the consolidated municipality would achieve savings of $3.2 million through scaled-down services, including the layoff of 15 government employees, nine of whom were police officers. However, the merger measure itself did not mandate these specific layoffs. Opponents challenged the cost-saving projections as unsubstantiated, voiced concerns about the differing zoning needs of the former borough and township, and pointed out the reduction in voter representation within a smaller governmental structure. This merger was the first in New Jersey since 1997, when [Pahaquarry Township, New Jersey](/Pahaquarry_Township,_New_Jersey) voted to consolidate with [Hardwick Township, New Jersey](/Hardwick_Township,_New_Jersey). [59] The consolidation officially took effect on January 1, 2013. [60]

Federal, State, and County Representation

Princeton is situated within the 12th Congressional District [61] and is part of New Jersey's 16th state legislative district. [62][63][64]

For the [119th United States Congress](/119th_United_States_Congress), [New Jersey's 12th congressional district](/New_Jersey's_12th_congressional_district) is represented by Bonnie Watson Coleman ([D](/Democratic_Party_(United_States))), who resides in [Ewing Township, New Jersey](/Ewing_Township,_New_Jersey). [65][66] The state of New Jersey is represented in the [United States Senate](/United_States_Senate) by Democrats Cory Booker ([Newark, New Jersey](/Newark,_New_Jersey), term ends 2027) and Andy Kim ([Moorestown, New Jersey](/Moorestown,_New_Jersey), term ends 2031). [67]

During the [2024-2025 session](/221st_New_Jersey_Legislature), New Jersey's 16th legislative district is represented in the [New Jersey Senate](/New_Jersey_Senate) by Andrew Zwicker ([D](/Democratic_Party_(United_States))) of [South Brunswick, New Jersey](/South_Brunswick,_New_Jersey). The [General Assembly](/New_Jersey_General_Assembly) representatives for this district are Mitchelle Drulis (D, [East Amwell Township, New Jersey](/East_Amwell_Township,_New_Jersey)) and Roy Freiman (D, [Hillsborough Township, New Jersey](/Hillsborough_Township,_New_Jersey)). [68]

