Education

Colleges and Universities

Princeton University's Cuyler and Walker Halls exemplify [Collegiate Gothic](/Collegiate_Gothic) architecture.
Princeton University's Fine Hall, home to its [Department of Mathematics](/Princeton_University_Department_of_Mathematics).
Fuld Hall, the primary facility of the [Institute for Advanced Study](/Institute_for_Advanced_Study).
The campus of Princeton University, recognized as one of the eight [Ivy League](/Ivy_League) institutions, once hosted [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein) as a lecturer.

[Princeton University](/Princeton_University), consistently ranked among the world's foremost [research](/Research) universities, is a defining characteristic of the community. Established in 1746 as the College of New Jersey, its relocation to Princeton occurred a decade later. The university's main campus is historically centered around [Nassau Street](/New_Jersey_Route_27) and extends southward. A satellite campus, the James Forrestal campus, is located in [Plainsboro Township, New Jersey](/Plainsboro_Township,_New_Jersey), and some of its athletic fields are situated in adjacent [West Windsor, New Jersey](/West_Windsor,_New_Jersey). Princeton University has held the top position in [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report)'s national university rankings for nine consecutive years as of 2024, and has also been recognized as a leading institution by [Forbes](/Forbes) and [The Wall Street Journal](/The_Wall_Street_Journal). [95][96][97]

[Princeton Theological Seminary](/Princeton_Theological_Seminary), the oldest seminary in America affiliated with the Presbyterian Church (USA), maintains its main academic campus within Princeton. Its residential housing facilities are located just outside Princeton in West Windsor Township. [98]

The [Institute for Advanced Study](/Institute_for_Advanced_Study) manages extensive grounds, known as the "Institute Woods," covering an area of 800 acres (320 ha). [99]

[Mercer County Community College], although not physically located within Princeton but rather in nearby [West Windsor, New Jersey](/West_Windsor,_New_Jersey), serves Princeton residents and the broader Mercer County community as a two-year public college. [100]

[Westminster Choir College], a music institution acquired by [Rider University](/Rider_University) in 1992, was founded on a substantial campus in Princeton in 1932. Prior to its establishment in Princeton, the college was based in [Dayton, Ohio](/Dayton,_Ohio), and subsequently had a brief period in [Ithaca, New York](/Ithaca,_New_York). [101] In 2012, Rider proposed an expansion of its parking facilities on the Princeton campus, which necessitated the removal of mature trees, a plan that faced significant opposition from local residents. [102][103] In 2019, Rider, whose main campus is in [Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey](/Lawrence_Township,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey), attempted to sell the Westminster Choir College campus in Princeton to a Chinese company. This proposed sale generated public outcry and was ultimately blocked. In 2020, Rider relocated all operations of Westminster Choir College from Princeton to its campus in [Lawrenceville, New Jersey](/Lawrenceville,_New_Jersey). The Princeton campus is now largely underutilized, with ongoing legal proceedings regarding its future and academic programs. [104] As of 2023, Princeton is leasing overflow parking at the Choir College from Rider for $1,000 per month, with the town subsequently reselling these parking rights to businesses, residents, and non-residents for $30 per month. The Choir College parking facilities are situated a few blocks' walk from the downtown area. [105][106]

Primary and Secondary Schools

Public Schools

[Princeton High School](/Princeton_High_School_(New_Jersey)).

The [Princeton Public Schools](/Princeton_Public_Schools) district serves students from [pre-kindergarten](/Pre-kindergarten) through [twelfth grade](/Twelfth_grade). [107] Students from [Cranbury Township, New Jersey](/Cranbury,_New_Jersey) attend the district's high school as part of a [sending/receiving relationship](/Sending/receiving_relationship). [108] For the 2020–21 academic year, the district comprised six schools and enrolled 3,740 students. It employed 341.0 classroom teachers on a [FTE](/Full-time_equivalent) basis, resulting in a [student–teacher ratio](/Student%E2%80%93teacher_ratio) of 11.0:1. [109] The schools within the district, with enrollment data for 2020–21 from the [National Center for Education Statistics](/National_Center_for_Education_Statistics), are:
Community Park School [111] with 332 students in grades K-5,
Johnson Park School [112] with 329 students in grades PreK-5,
Littlebrook School [113] with 342 students in grades K-5,
Riverside School [114] with 289 students in grades PreK-5,
Princeton Middle School [115] with 803 students in grades 6-8, and
[Princeton High School](/Princeton_High_School_(New_Jersey)) [116] with 1,555 students in grades 9–12. [117][118][119][120][121]

[New Jersey Monthly] magazine ranked [Princeton High School](/Princeton_High_School_(New_Jersey)) as the 20th best high school in New Jersey in its 2018 "Top Public High Schools" rankings. [122] In 2024, the school was also ranked as the 33rd best high school in New Jersey by [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report). [123] Furthermore, [Niche (company)](/Niche_(company)) placed [Princeton High School](/Princeton_High_School_(New_Jersey)) at number 147 in its "2025 Best Public High Schools in America" rankings. [124]

In the early 1990s, a redistricting process was implemented between the Community Park and Johnson Park School districts due to increased student populations in both areas, attributed to residential development. Concerns were also raised regarding the predominantly white, affluent student body at Johnson Park (JP) and the more racially and economically diverse student population at Community Park (CP). Consequently, sections of the affluent Western Section neighborhood were rezoned to CP, while parts of the racially and economically diverse John Witherspoon neighborhood were rezoned to JP.

The [Princeton Charter School](/Princeton_Charter_School), which serves students in grades K–8, operates under a [charter](/Charter_school) granted by the commissioner of the [New Jersey Department of Education](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Education). As a public school, it functions independently of the Princeton Regional Schools and is funded on a per-student basis through locally raised tax revenues. [125]

Eighth-grade students from across Mercer County are eligible to apply for admission to the high school programs offered by the [Mercer County Technical Schools](/Mercer_County_Technical_Schools). This county-wide vocational school district provides full-time career and technical education at its Health Sciences Academy, STEM Academy, and Academy of Culinary Arts, with no tuition fees for enrolled students. [126][127]

Private Schools

Private educational institutions located within Princeton include [The Lewis School of Princeton](/The_Lewis_School_of_Princeton), [Princeton Day School](/Princeton_Day_School), [Princeton Friends School](/Princeton_Friends_School), the [Hun School of Princeton](/Hun_School_of_Princeton), and [Princeton International School of Mathematics and Science](/Princeton_International_School_of_Mathematics_and_Science) (PRISMS).

[St. Paul's Catholic School](/St._Paul's_School_(Princeton,_New_Jersey)), established in 1878 and catering to students from pre-school through 8th grade, is the oldest and only coeducational Catholic school in the area. It operates alongside [Princeton Academy of the Sacred Heart](/Princeton_Academy_of_the_Sacred_Heart) (K–8, all male) and [Stuart Country Day School of the Sacred Heart](/Stuart_Country_Day_School) (coeducational for Pre-K, and all-female K–12), both of which are supervised by the [Roman Catholic Diocese of Trenton](/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Trenton). [128]

Several schools with Princeton addresses are situated outside the municipality's formal boundaries. These include the [Wilberforce School](/Wilberforce_School), [Chapin School](/Chapin_School_(New_Jersey)) in [Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey](/Lawrence_Township,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey), [Princeton Junior School](/Lawrence_Township,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey) also in Lawrence Township, the French-American School of Princeton, the Laurel School of Princeton, the Waldorf School of Princeton, YingHua International School, Princeton Latin Academy in [Hopewell, New Jersey](/Hopewell,_New_Jersey), Princeton Montessori School in [Montgomery Township, New Jersey](/Montgomery_Township,_New_Jersey), Eden Institute in [West Windsor, New Jersey](/West_Windsor,_New_Jersey), and the now-defunct [American Boychoir School](/American_Boychoir_School) in [Plainsboro Township, New Jersey](/Plainsboro_Township,_New_Jersey).

Public Libraries

The [Princeton Public Library]'s current facility, located on Witherspoon Street, was inaugurated in April 2004 as part of the ongoing downtown redevelopment initiative. It replaced a building that dated back to 1966. The library itself was founded in 1909. [129]

Miscellaneous Education

The [Princeton Community Japanese Language School] conducts weekend Japanese language classes for children of Japanese citizens residing abroad, adhering to the standards set by the [Ministry of Education, Culture, Sports, Science and Technology (MEXT)](/Ministry_of_Education,_Culture,_Sports,_Science_and_Technology) (MEXT). The school also offers classes for individuals learning Japanese as a second language. While the main administrative office of the school is located in Princeton, its Sunday operations are based in Memorial Hall at [Rider University](/Rider_University) in Lawrence Township, Mercer County, New Jersey. [130] Courses are delivered at Memorial Hall on the Rider University campus. [131]

The Princeton Learning Cooperative provides support for student-directed learning, functioning as a hybrid model of homeschooling and traditional schooling for teenagers. [132][133]

Infrastructure

Transportation

Roads and Highways

As of May 2010, Princeton had a total of 126.95 miles (204.31 km) of roadways. Of this total, 118.36 miles (190.48 km) were maintained by the municipality, 3.93 miles (6.32 km) by Mercer County, and 8.66 miles (13.94 km) by the [New Jersey Department of Transportation](/New_Jersey_Department_of_Transportation). [134]

Several major roadways traverse Princeton, including [U.S. Route 206](/U.S._Route_206) [135][136] and [Route 27](/New_Jersey_Route_27), [137] along with County Routes [583](/County_Route_583_(New_Jersey)), [138] [526](/County_Route_526_(New_Jersey))/[571](/County_Route_571_(New_Jersey)) (widely known as Washington Road), [139] and [533](/County_Route_533_(New_Jersey)). [140]

Additional major roads accessible from outside the municipality include [U.S. Route 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_New_Jersey) (located in Lawrence Township, West Windsor, and South Brunswick), [Interstate 287](/Interstate_287) (in Franklin Township), [Interstate 295](/Interstate_295_(Delaware%E2%80%93Pennsylvania)) (in Lawrence Township), and the [New Jersey Turnpike](/New_Jersey_Turnpike)/[Interstate 95](/Interstate_95_in_New_Jersey) (in South Brunswick). The nearest Turnpike exits are Interchange 8A in [Monroe Township, Middlesex County, New Jersey](/Monroe_Township,_Middlesex_County,_New_Jersey), Interchange 8 in [East Windsor, New Jersey](/East_Windsor,_New_Jersey), and Interchange 7A in [Robbinsville Township, New Jersey](/Robbinsville_Township,_New_Jersey).

Several proposed highway projects surrounding Princeton were ultimately canceled. The [Somerset Freeway (I-95)](/Somerset_Freeway) was planned to pass just outside the municipality, connecting to Hopewell to the south and Franklin to the north. This project was canceled in 1980. [New Jersey Route 92](/New_Jersey_Route_92) was intended to address the lack of limited-access highways serving the greater Princeton area. This road was slated to begin at Route 1 near Ridge Road in South Brunswick and terminate at Exit 8A of the Turnpike. However, this project was canceled in 2006.

Public Transportation

The "Dinky" train at the [Princeton Branch](/Princeton_Branch) platform, located at Princeton Junction.

Princeton is situated roughly equidistant from [New York City](/New_York_City) and [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia). Since the 19th century, it has maintained rail connectivity to both cities via the [Princeton Branch](/Princeton_Branch) rail line, which connects to the nearby [Princeton Junction station](/Princeton_Junction_station) on [Amtrak]'s [Northeast Corridor](/Northeast_Corridor). [141][142] The [Princeton train station](/Princeton_station_(NJ_Transit)) was relocated from beneath Blair Hall to a more southerly position on University Place in 1918, [141] and was moved further southeast in 2013. [143] Commuting from Princeton to New York City became a regular occurrence following World War II. [144] While Amtrak travel times are comparable to both New York and Philadelphia, the commuter train journey to New York, operated by [NJ Transit](/NJ_Transit) on the [Northeast Corridor Line](/Northeast_Corridor_Line), is generally faster than the equivalent train service to Philadelphia, which requires a transfer to [SEPTA](/SEPTA) trains in [Trenton, New Jersey](/Trenton,_New_Jersey). NJ Transit provides a shuttle service connecting the Princeton and Princeton Junction stations; this train is colloquially known as the "Dinky" [142] and has also been referred to as the "PJ&B" (standing for "Princeton Junction and Back"). [145] The train typically consists of two cars, though sometimes only one is utilized.

NJ Transit operates bus services to [Trenton, New Jersey](/Trenton,_New_Jersey) via the [606](/606_(New_Jersey_bus)) route and provides local service on route [605](/605_(New_Jersey_bus)). [146][147]

Coach USA's [Suburban Transit](/Suburban_Transit) offers frequent daily bus services to Midtown Manhattan on the 100 route, and weekday rush-hour services to Downtown Manhattan on the 600 route. [148]

Princeton and Princeton University jointly operate the FreeB and [Tiger Transit](/Tiger_Transit) local bus services within the municipality. [149]

Air Travel

[Princeton Airport](/Princeton_Airport_(New_Jersey)) is a public airport located 3 miles (4.8 km) north of Downtown Princeton in [Montgomery Township, New Jersey](/Montgomery_Township,_New_Jersey). The private [Forrestal Airport](/List_of_airports_in_New_Jersey) was situated on Princeton University property, 2 miles (3.2 km) east of the main campus, operating from the early 1950s until the early 1990s.

The closest commercial airport is [Trenton-Mercer Airport](/Trenton-Mercer_Airport) in [Ewing Township, New Jersey](/Ewing_Township,_New_Jersey), approximately 15 miles (24 km) from the center of Princeton. This airport is served by [Frontier Airlines] with nonstop flights to and from 17 cities. Other major airports in the vicinity include [Newark Liberty International Airport](/Newark_Liberty_International_Airport), located 39 miles (63 km) away, and [Philadelphia International Airport](/Philadelphia_International_Airport), situated 52 miles (84 km) away.

Healthcare

[Penn Medicine Princeton Medical Center](/Penn_Medicine_Princeton_Medical_Center)

[Penn Medicine Princeton Medical Center](/Penn_Medicine_Princeton_Medical_Center), often abbreviated as "PMC," is a regional hospital and healthcare network located in the neighboring [Plainsboro Township, New Jersey](/Plainsboro_Township,_New_Jersey). The hospital serves the wider Princeton area in [Central Jersey](/Central_Jersey). It is owned by the [Penn Medicine Health System](/Perelman_School_of_Medicine_at_the_University_of_Pennsylvania) and is the only hospital of its kind within the state of New Jersey. [150] PMC is a 355-bed [non-profit](/Non-profit), [tertiary](/Tertiary_care) care, and [academic medical center](/Teaching_hospital). It functions as a primary university hospital for the [Robert Wood Johnson Medical School](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_Medical_School) of [Rutgers University](/Rutgers_University) [152] and is equipped with a helipad for critical patient transport to and from other medical facilities via PennStar. [153] The hospital was previously situated in Princeton on Witherspoon Street until May 2012, when its new facility opened off [U.S. Route 1](/U.S._Route_1_in_New_Jersey) in Plainsboro. [154] The new hospital was designed through a collaborative venture between [HOK (firm)](/HOK_(firm)) and [RMJM Hiller](/RMJM). [155][156]

Other healthcare facilities and networks accessible to Princeton residents include the [Hamilton Township, Mercer County, New Jersey](/Hamilton_Township,_Mercer_County,_New_Jersey) division and the [New Brunswick, New Jersey](/New_Brunswick,_New_Jersey) division of [Robert Wood Johnson University Hospital (RWJUH)](/Robert_Wood_Johnson_University_Hospital), as well as [Saint Peter's University Hospital](/Saint_Peter's_University_Hospital), also located in New Brunswick. The [Frist Campus Center](/Frist_Campus_Center) at [Princeton University](/Princeton_University) [a] served as the visual backdrop for the fictional Princeton-Plainsboro Teaching Hospital in the television series [House (TV series)](/House_(TV_series)). [157]

