In Popular Culture

• See also: [Princeton University § In fiction](/Princeton_University)

Film

Princeton served as the setting for the [Academy Award](/Academy_Awards)-winning film [A Beautiful Mind](/A_Beautiful_Mind_(film)), which depicted the life of the schizophrenic mathematician [John Nash](/John_Forbes_Nash_Jr._(mathematician)). While much of the filming took place in central New Jersey, including some Princeton locations, many scenes portraying "Princeton" were actually filmed at Fordham University's Rose Hill campus in the Bronx. [citation needed]

The 1994 film [I.Q.](/I.Q._(film)), starring [Meg Ryan](/Meg_Ryan), [Tim Robbins](/Tim_Robbins), and [Walter Matthau](/Walter_Matthau) as [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein), was also set in Princeton and filmed in the surrounding area. The film includes some geographical liberties, such as Matthau viewing characters kissing on the [Princeton Battlefield](/Princeton_Battlefield) through a telescope from the roof of "Princeton Hospital." [340]

Historical films that used Princeton as a setting but were not filmed there include [Wilson (1944 film)](/Wilson_(1944_film)), a biographical film about Woodrow Wilson released in 1944.

In his 1989 independent feature film [Stage Fright](/Stage_Fright_(1989)), filmmaker [Brad Mays](/Brad_Mays) filmed a drama class scene in the Princeton High School auditorium, utilizing PHS students as extras. On October 18, 2013, Mays' feature documentary [I Grew Up in Princeton](/I_Grew_Up_in_Princeton) premiered at Princeton High School. This film, described by a local Princeton newspaper as a "deeply personal 'coming-of-age story' that yields perspective on the role of perception in a town that was split racially, economically and sociologically," [341] offers a portrayal of life in the renowned university town during the turbulent period spanning the late 1960s through the early 1970s.

Scenes from the initial part of [Across the Universe (film)](/Across_the_Universe_(film)) (2007) were filmed on the campus of Princeton University.

Portions of the film [Transformers: Revenge of the Fallen](/Transformers:_Revenge_of_the_Fallen) were shot in Princeton. Megan Fox and Shia LaBeouf filmed scenes on the Princeton University campus over two days during the summer of 2008.

Scenes from the 2008 movie [The Happening (2008 film)](/The_Happening_(2008_film)) were filmed in Princeton.

TV and Radio

The 1938 [Orson Welles](/Orson_Welles) radio broadcast of [The War of the Worlds](/The_War_of_the_Worlds_(radio)) is partially set in nearby [Grover's Mill, New Jersey](/Grover's_Mill,_New_Jersey), and features a fictional professor from Princeton University as a main character. However, the narrative action does not directly take place within Princeton itself.

The 1980 television miniseries [Oppenheimer (TV miniseries)](/Oppenheimer_(TV_miniseries)) is partly set in Princeton.

[George Lucas]'s [The Young Indiana Jones Chronicles](/The_Young_Indiana_Jones_Chronicles) television series, a spin-off of the [Indiana Jones](/Indiana_Jones) film franchise, features Princeton in three episodes. Princeton is depicted as the hometown of the main character, [archaeologist](/Archaeologist) and adventurer [Indiana Jones (character)](/Indiana_Jones_(character)), whose father, [Henry Jones, Sr.](/Henry_Jones,_Sr.), is a university professor. Princeton plays a prominent role in the episodes "Spring Break Adventure" and "Winds of Change," although the Princeton scenes were filmed in [Wilmington, North Carolina](/Wilmington,_North_Carolina) and [Durham, North Carolina](/Durham,_North_Carolina). [342][343]

The television show [House (TV series)](/House_(TV_series)) was set in Princeton, at the fictional Princeton-Plainsboro Teaching Hospital. Establishing shots of the hospital featured the [Frist Campus Center](/Frist_Campus_Center) of [Princeton University](/Princeton_University). The actual University Medical Center of Princeton at Plainsboro commenced operations on May 22, 2012, exactly one day after the series finale of House aired. [344]

Literature

[F. Scott Fitzgerald]'s debut novel, [This Side of Paradise](/This_Side_of_Paradise), is a semi-autobiographical account of his experiences at Princeton University.

The presence of numerous nationally and internationally recognized writers within Princeton University's Creative Writing program has established the community as a significant hub for contemporary literature.

Many of [Richard Ford]'s novels are set in Haddam, New Jersey, a fictionalized representation of Princeton. [232]

[Joyce Carol Oates]'s 2004 novel *Take Me, Take Me With You* (published under the pseudonym Lauren Kelly) is set in Princeton. [345]

New Jersey author [Judy Blume](/Judy_Blume) set her novel *Superfudge* in Princeton. [346]

Music

All members of the band [Blues Traveler](/Blues_Traveler), along with [Chris Barron](/Chris_Barron), the lead singer of the [Spin Doctors](/Spin_Doctors), hail from Princeton and were childhood friends. [347]

